<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister on `Deadline' for DPRK Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister on `Deadline' for DPRK Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1704232394 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2205 GMT 17 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1704232394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kim Chin-su from Brussels] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu announced that the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] set the deadline for 
North Korea's acceptance of additional nuclear inspections at 
mid-May and that just in case North Korea exceeds the deadline, 
the IAEA will soon report to the UN Security Council. 
  Foreign Minister Han, who is in Belgium, said: Although many 
experts believe North Korea will accept the additional nuclear 
inspections in late April, in early May, or in mid-May, the IAEA 
has set the deadline for North Korea's acceptance at around 
mid-May. 
  Foreign Minister Han said: The IAEA has not set a definite 
date in mid-May as its deadline for North Korea to accept the 
additional inspections, but it will report to the UN Security 
Council when it is believed North Korea has exceeded the 
deadline. As a result, the North Korean nuclear issue will 
again be handled by the UN Security Council, as was the case in 
the UN Security Council presidential statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

