<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Excludes Intervention on DPRK Loggers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Excludes Intervention on DPRK Loggers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1604080294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0749 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1604080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 16 (YONHAP) -- Russia hopes to handle 
resettlement of North Korean loggers in Siberia without 
intervention by an international organization, Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev said Friday. 
  Radio Moscow quoted him as saying that his country will be 
strict with human rights protection requirements in renewing the 
logging contract with North Korea. 
  Moscow should consider applying Russia's domestic laws on 
all 
people living on Russian soil, and their human rights have to be 
guaranteed at maximum level, Kozyrev said according to Radio 
Moscow. 
  But he indicated his country was against intervention by a 
third party, saying Moscow plans to resolve the issue without 
participation by international organizations. 
  The Seoul Government announced Friday it will accept all 
North Korean loggers who wish to settle in South Korea. Some 
100 North Koreans, virtually trapped inside logging camps in 
Siberia where escapees tell of rampant beating and near 
starvation, have asked to be sent to Seoul. 
  Seoul officials said they want to refer to the UN High 
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in arranging their 
resettlement. 
  The logging contract between Russia and North Korea was to 
expire at the end of last year but the two sides are still 
negotiating renewal after Moscow demanded human rights condition 
improvement inside the camps. 
  Next negotiation is expected in Moscow within first half of 
this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

