<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul To Accept DPRK Loggers From Siberia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul To Accept DPRK Loggers From Siberia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1604025194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0245 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1604025194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 16 (YONHAP) -- More than 100 North 
Korean loggers in Russia will be brought to South Korea, 
presidential spokesman Chu Ton-sik said Saturday [16 April]. 
  Chu made the announcement one day after Seoul said it had 
decided to accept all escapees from North Korean logging camps 
in Siberia wishing to settle in South Korea. 
  "As a result, the government will bring to South Korea more 
than 100 North Korean loggers who have applied for settlement in 
South Korea at the South Korean Embassy in Moscow," Chu said. 
  Chu also said the government expects more escapees from 
North 
Korean logging camps to seek refuge in the South "since we have 
decided to accept them." 
  "Even in that situation, the government will accept all 
North 
Korean loggers with the exception of those with serious 
problems," he said. 
  Chu clarified that "those with serious problems" include 
criminals such as "infamous offenders." 
  The Seoul government understands, however, that most of the 
"infamous" offenders committed "crimes" because they were hungry 
and tried to steal food, he said. 
  The South Korean Embassy in Moscow has conducted an initial 
screening of the North Korean loggers seeking refuge in the 
South and found almost no "infamous offenders," Chu said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

