<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Willing To Talk With DPRK About Loggers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul Willing To Talk With DPRK About Loggers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1804004294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0028 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1804004294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 18 (YONHAP) -- The government plans to 
negotiate directly with North Korea if Pyongyang makes an issue 
out of Seoul's decision to resettle fleeing North Korean loggers 
in the South. 
  A senior government official said Sunday there was a strong 
possibility that North Korea would officially broach Seoul's 
decision last week to give North Korean loggers refuge in the 
South. 
  "In that case, the government plans to push direct 
negotiations with North Korea on this problem," he said. 
  An estimated 500 North Koreans are said to have escaped from 
Pyongyang-run logging camps in Siberia, many of whom are hiding 
in various parts of Russia to elude North Korean agents while 
seeking refuge in South Korea. 
  The official, who declined to be identified, noted that when 
many East Germans tried to escape to West Germany, the Bonn 
government solved the problem by negotiating directly with East 
Germany. 
  The government will cooperate with Russia and the United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in the process of 
settling the North Korean loggers in the South, he said. 
  But there is a possibility that North Korea, insisting the 
loggers are "criminals," will demand their repatriation. The 
government has decided to prepare for this eventuality by 
checking the background of all North Korean loggers applying for 
refuge in the South, he said. 
  In addition, the government will introduce a procedure 
allowing the UNHCR to confirm whether the loggers indeed want to 
leave their country or settle in nations other than South Korea, 
in order to prevent Pyongyang from leveling charges of 
kidnapping against Seoul, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

