<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Red Cross Urges Repatriation of Two Men </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Red Cross Urges Repatriation of Two Men </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1904084694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0800 GMT 19 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1904084694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The North Korean side sent a telephone message to 
our side on 19 April demanding the repatriation of Kim In-so and 
Ham Se-hwan, who have not converted from communism over a long 
period of time. 
  Yi Song-ho, acting chairman of the Central Committee of the 
North Korean Red Cross Society, North Korea sent a telephone 
message to Kang Yong-hun, chairman of the ROK National Red 
Cross, on 19 April, pointing out that for the South side to 
reject the North side's demand to repatriate the two men, which 
has happened on two occasions, runs counter to the humanitarian 
ideology of the Red Cross. 
  Today's message by North Korea is being interpreted as a 
countermeasure to the fact that the South side has started to 
show interest in the North Korean humanitarian issue, such as 
the South Korean Government's decision to allow North Korean 
loggers who escaped from logging camps in Russia to defect to 
South Korea. 

</TEXT>

