<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Currency Holdings Limit Abolished </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Currency Holdings Limit Abolished </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1904011094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0031 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904011094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 19 (YONHAP) -- The Ministry of Finance 
decided Tuesday to scrap the regulation restricting an 
individual's foreign currency holdings to 10,000 U.S. dollars 
beginning June 1, setting no possession limit. 
  The Ministry, however, called on those who have over 50,000 
dollars to report to the authorities, citing the need to have 
correct information on the country's foreign currency reserves 
for effective implementation of economic policies. 
  In another effort to internationalize the nation's economy, 
the Ministry allowed businesses to use Korean won equivalent up 
to 300,000 dollars, compared to the present limit of 100,000 
dollars, in settling import, export and reinsurance accounts. 
  The Ministry also allowed businesses to spend Korean won in 
settling freight and insurance accounts incurred through the 
export and import of goods. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

