<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reports on Labor Strikes, Ethnic Unrest </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reports on Labor Strikes, Ethnic Unrest </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Troops in Medan on Alert </H4>

<F P=102> BK1804144194 Jakarta ANTARA in English 1417 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1804144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, Apr 18 (ANTARA) -- Chairman of the 
Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry Aburizal Bakrie 
affirmed that employers in Medan are willing to increase the 
wages of their employees but only if their demands are 
reasonable. 
  The workers' demand for a pay increase to 7,000 rupiah 
(around US$3.33) per day is unreasonable compared to the 
regional minimum wage of only 3,100 rupiah per day (around 
US$1.5), Bakrie told a press conference after a meeting with 
President Suharto at Merdeka Palace [Presidential Palace] Monday. 
  The conflict began in Medan on Thursday when more than 
10,000 
workers went on strike to demand higher wages and holiday bonus 
payments. The demonstration ended in a riot following the death 
of one worker. More than a hundred shops were ransacked and 
dozens of cars were set ablaze. 
  Indonesian police and troops in armoured cars remain on 
alert, guarding Medan's industrial areas, particularly on the 
city's outskirts where most of the rioting took place. 

</TEXT>

