<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senior Officials Discuss Cambodian Allegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Senior Officials Discuss Cambodian Allegations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1504135694 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 1200 GMT 
15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1504135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>
<F P=105>  Thai </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A meeting on Thai-Cambodian border problems was 
held at the Foreign Ministry today. The attendants were Foreign 
Minister Squadron Leader Prasong Sunsiri; Interior Minister 
General Chawalit Yongchaiyut; Gen. Charan Kunlawanit, National 
Security Council secretary general; Navy Commander Admiral 
Prachet Siridet; and other officials concerned. 
  Reporting afterwards, the foreign minister said the meeting 
discussed problems along the Thai-Cambodian border and 
retaliatory measures against Cambodia. The Foreign Ministry 
will today send a letter to Cambodian Prime Ministers Prince 
Norodom Ranariddh and Hun Sen regarding the Cambodian 
allegations about Thai support for the Khmer Rouge. The letter 
will clarify what has occurred and point out that Thailand is 
basically complying with the Paris Agreement. It will confirm 
that Thailand has not supported any particular Cambodian group, 
as well as not having supplied weapons to the Khmer Rouge. 
  The foreign minister said Thailand will not accept further 
Cambodian refugees. The Foreign Ministry will encourage 
Cambodia to promptly establish within one year a safety zone for 
refugees fleeing the fighting. The foreign minister said the 
Thai military will take drastic action to deal with shelling of 
Thai territory by the Khmer Rouge or Cambodian Government forces. 

</TEXT>

