<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Chief Discusses Cambodian Border `Warning' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Chief Discusses Cambodian Border `Warning' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1704114194 Bangkok THE SUNDAY NATION in English 17 Apr 94 
p A2 </F>

<F P=103> BK1704114194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE SUNDAY NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Army Commander-in-Chief Gen Wimon Wongwanit was 
guarded yesterday in his reaction to Phnom Penh's warning it 
would attack Khmer Rouge tanks found on Thai soil, saying only 
that the military was responsible for safety and security along 
the border. 
  Wimon refused to make any comment about exactly how the Army 
would respond to any possible encroachment on Thai territory by 
Phnom Penh forces. 
  He repeated Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri's comment on 
Friday that the allegations by Cambodian leaders that the Khmer 
Rouge was operating from Thai soil were groundless. 
  Cambodian Co-Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh last 
week alleged Khmer Rouge tanks had fired from inside Thailand at 
Phnom Penh government forces in Pailin. 
  On Thursday the Prince warned that his forces might attack 
the Khmer Rouge tanks even if they were on Thai territory and 
that he was losing patience over what he called Thailand's 
continued failure to crack down on Khmer Rouge forces. 
  "If you say they are not on your territory, please don't 
make 
any protest if we violate your territory. We don't intend to do 
that," he reportedly said. 
  The Khmer Rouge are universally held responsible for the 
deaths of more than one million Cambodians during the Pol Pot 
reign of terror from 1974 to 1979. 
  Wimon on Friday met Foreign Minister Prasong, Interior 
Minister Gen Chawalit Yongchaiyut, Defence Minister Wichit 
Sukmak and senior military officials to discuss the charges. 
  Meanwhile, Army spokesman Col Phalangkun Klahan insisted 
that 
Thailand has never allowed any foreign troops onto its territory 
and that Prince Norodom's allegation was unfounded and unfair to 
Thailand. 
  He also said the Army has not been involved in Cambodia's 
internal affairs or provided assistance to the Maoist faction 
since the signing of the Paris Peace Accord in August 1991. 
  "Cambodia should think of its relationship with Thailand 
before making accusations of this sort," he said. 
  Phalangkun also said the Army would give an abrupt and harsh 
response if Cambodian forces are found on Thai soil. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

