<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Okinawan Governor `Envies' Subic Bay Conversion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Okinawan Governor `Envies' Subic Bay Conversion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504145094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1427 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Manila, April 15 KYODO -- Okinawa Governor Masahide 
Ota said Friday [15 April] the conversion of the former United 
States naval base at Subic Bay into a commercial and industrial 
free port is a good example for Okinawa to follow. 
  Ota, who is on a six-day visit to the Philippines, told 
reporters during a visit to Subic that he "envies" its 
conversion, which followed the U.S. withdrawal of forces from 
the port in 1992. 
  Subic Bay was once the largest U.S. overseas naval base. 
  Ota said he could foresee a bustling commercial and 
industrial free port in Subic 10 years from now, adding, "I 
really envy the successful conversion of the Subic naval base 
into a commercial district." 
  Subic is about 70 kilometers north of Manila. 
  The Okinawan archipelago in southern Japan, still plays host 
to a strong U.S. military presence. 

</TEXT>

