<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Student Protest Against Patriots Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Student Protest Against Patriots Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1904111394 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1009 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1904111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 1009 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This news is just in. College students in Seoul and 
Kwangju Districts have staged violent anti-U.S. demonstrations, 
chanting slogans such as "We hate Patriots!" and "We hate Perry!" 
  According to Seoul radio reports, on 19 April, the college 
students in Seoul and Kwangju waged violent demonstration 
struggles, protesting the arrival of Patriot missiles in the 
port of Pusan and U.S. Defense Secretary Perry's junket to Seoul. 
  In Seoul, a group of students, breaking a tight police 
cordon, waged a demonstration struggle in front of the U.S. 
Embassy in Seoul, chanting anti-U.S. slogans with placards such 
as "We hate Patriots!" and "We hate Perry!" 
  In the meantime, on the morning of 19 April, some 500 
members 
of the Kwangju Chonnam District General Student Council staged a 
protest rally in front of the Kwangju American Cultural Center. 
Branding the U.S. defense secretary's junket to Seoul and the 
deployment of Patriot missiles to South Korea as a criminal act 
of increasing the danger of war, the students threw some 200 
bottles of paint at the American Cultural Center building. 
  The puppet clique, perplexed by the students' strong 
protests, mobilized numerous combat policemen to brutally 
suppress the student demonstrators. However, the demonstrators 
did not yield to this and continued their struggle, chanting 
slogans calling for the withdrawal of the U.S. imperialist 
aggression forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

