<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Analyzes U.S. `Scheme' for War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Analyzes U.S. `Scheme' for War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1904063294 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0508 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904063294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Military Analyst on Scheme of U.S. Military for New Korean </F>
War" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 19 (KCNA) -- NODONG SINMUN today 
comes out with a military analyst's commentary hitting out at 
the scheme of the U.S. military to start another war in Korea. 
  The U.S. Defense Secretary, William Perry, some time ago let 
loose an impudent blast, threatening that the U.S. "will not 
rule out a preemptive strike" at the DPRK over its fictitious 
"nuclear suspicion." 
  Signalled by this, the U.S. military is making a massive 
shipment of military hardware including Patriot missiles to 
South Korea, massing its naval force in the waters around Korea 
and frequently staging military drills with the South Korean 
puppets in their intensified military actions. 
  Viewing this as dangerous provocative acts intended to carry 
into practice the war scenario which it had rounded off through 
the "Team Spirit" joint war games from long ago for the purpose 
of stifling the socialism of the DPRK with "strength," the 
military analyst says: 
  The escalation of the U.S. military actions against the DPRK 
is an offspring of the strategy of the expansion of arms market 
which had been worked out through "back-door dealings" between 
the U.S. administration and the U.S. war industrial monopolies. 
The officials of the U.S. administration are, without 
exception, servants of big monopolies, especially munitions 
industrial monopolies. Hence their manoeuvres to ignite a war 
on the Korean peninsula and fatten the munitions industrial 
monopolies which find themselves in a sorry plight with the 
shrinkage of the arms market after the end of the cold war. 
  Motivated by these interests, the U.S. military raised the 
curtain of the Korean war scenario and buckled down to its full- 
scale promotion. 
  Now a very grave situation which might touch off a war for a 
slightest casual factor is prevailing on the Korean peninsula. 
  The U.S. military is shameless enough to harp on "a patient 
diplomatic solution," describing its harebrained anti-DPRK 
military actions as "for self-defense." 
  It is well-known a fact that the United States has down 
through history cried for "a diplomatic solution" before 
invading other countries and then tried to justify its military 
actions. The "active and patient diplomatic solution" vis-a-vis 
the DPRK advertised by the U.S. is nothing but a war diplomacy 
to bring it to its knees and overpower it by armed invasion and 
the socalled "defense" on the lips of the U.S. is no more than a 
smokescreen to conceal its bellicose and aggressive nature. 
  Behind the smokescreen of "self-defense" the United States 
is 
scheming to mass armed forces in and around South Korea and 
venture a military action against the DPRK. 
  But they are committing a mistake. 
  No strong arm works with us. Should the United States and 
its lackeys dare provoke a war, we will answer it with a 
decisive counter blow to defend our socialist system and the 
dignity of our republic. 
  The United States would be well advised not to act rashly or 
forget the bitter lesson of the past Korean war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

