<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Repatriation of Former POW's in ROK Demanded </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Repatriation of Former POW's in ROK Demanded </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    ROK Journal Cited </H4>

<F P=102> SK1904102094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1006 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 19 (KCNA) -- The first and second 
issues of the South Korean magazine HUMAN RIGHTS of 1994 
reported that the South Korean headquarters for the promotion of 
the repatriation of old Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan which was 
formed in June last year has conducted brisk activities 
demanding the repatriation of these two old men, long-term 
prisoners who have refused to be converted. 
  This headquarters involves the human rights committee of the 
Council of Christian Churches, human rights committees of Roman 
Catholic and Buddhist organisations, the bar association for a 
Democratic Society, the Council of Family Movement for Realising 
Democracy and other civilian human rights organisations, and 
human rights committees and dissident organisations in Taejon 
and Kwangju. 
  After its inauguration, it sent appeals to the South Korean 
"minister of the Unification Board" and presidents of the 
International Red Cross and of the South Korean Red Cross, 
strongly demanding the repatriation of the two unconverted 
long-term prisoners to the northern half of Korea. 
  A statement of the headquarters carried in the magazine 
HUMAN 
RIGHTS said old Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan must have been 
repatriated at the time of exchange of POWs according to the 
Geneva Conventions because they were taken prisoners during the 
war, but they had been submitted for trial by the 
"court-martial" and made to suffer in prison for scores of 
years. It strongly urged the South Korean authorities to return 
the two old men to the North as soon as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

