<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Repatriation of Former POW's in ROK Demanded </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Repatriation of Former POW's in ROK Demanded </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Repatriation Committee Said Formed </H4>

<F P=102> SK1904115194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1022 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 19 (KCNA) -- A committee for the 
promotion of the repatriation of old Kim Yong-tae, a long-term 
prisoner who has refused to be converted, is now active in South 
Korea, according to the South Korean magazine "HUMAN RIGHTS" 
Nos. 1 and 2 of 1994. 
  Hailing from Chongju, North Phyongan Province, he 
volunteered 
to join in the People's Army at the age of 18 when the U.S. 
imperialists unleashed the war of aggression against Korea in 
1950. 
  He was wounded on the front and taken prisoner. He should 
have been repatriated to the northern half of Korea according to 
the Geneva Convention. But, he has not been sent back to the 
North due to the unlawful acts of the South Korean puppet clique 
and had to serve a prison term of 33 years in South Korea for 
his refusal to be converted. 
  A committee for the promotion of the repatriation of old Kim 
Yong-tae centering on a Christian organisation was formed early 
in December last year. 
  According to the magazine, Kim Yong-tae in a recent letter 
to 
the president of the International Red Cross said that although 
he was released from prison, he was making his living by 
toilsome work for many hours at a rough-work place as a lonely 
and old disabled man without his relatives, chained by the "law 
on supervision for public peace." He asked for help, saying that 
it was his cherished desire to meet his relatives once before he 
died. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

