<DOCNO> FBIS4-6247 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas075_c_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Repatriation of Former POW's in ROK Demanded </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Repatriation of Former POW's in ROK Demanded </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Red Cross Group Sends Letter </H4>

<F P=102> SK1904113294 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1100 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 19 (KCNA) -- Yi Song-ho, acting 
chairman of the Central Committee of the DPRK Red Cross Society, 
in a letter sent today to Kang Yong-hun, president of the South 
Korean Red Cross, urged the South side once again to show a 
positive response at an early date to the reasonable demand of 
the North for an immediate repatriation of Kim In-so and Ham 
Se-hwan, prisoners of war. 
  The letter says: 
  The South side in a telephone message December 3 last year 
turned down the reasonable demand of the North for the 
repatriation of Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan, contending that they 
did not belong to the category of prisoners of war because of 
their guerrilla activities and acceptance of nationality. Its 
wrong attitude and assertion are quite contrary to the 
humanitarianism of Red Cross. 
  According to international law, those who are arrested by 
the 
warring party while in action are to be considered prisoners of 
war, be they soldiers or guerrillas. Therefore, Kim In-so and 
Ham Se-hwan must be treated as prisoners of war and should have 
been repatriated under the Korean Armistice Agreement. 
  The South side's refusal of their repatriation on the ground 
of their nationality acceptance shows that it acts contrary to 
the humanitarianism of Red Cross, manipulated by some seditious 
forces that dislike national reconciliation and unity. 
  As you know, Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan do not want to live 
in 
South Korea and have already asked the International Committee 
of the Red Cross to help them in their repatriation to the North. 
  The two daughters of Kim In-so, the sister of Ham Se-hwan in 
her eighties and other family members and relatives in the 
northern half of the country are earnestly wishing their 
repatriation to the North. 
  We hold that the repatriation of Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan, 
who are undeniably prisoners of war, must be realised at an 
early date as required by the Korean Armistice Agreement and the 
international law on prisoners of war, unhindered by any pretext 
or condition. 

</TEXT>

