<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., Japan `Examine' Sanctions Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., Japan `Examine' Sanctions Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1904080894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0754 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904080894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 (YONHAP) -- The United States has 
hinted that if North Korea refuses to allow additional nuclear 
checks before the end of April, it will go its own way to impose 
sanctions on the Stalinist state even before the United Nations 
adopts any resolution and seek Japanese cooperation in that 
case, the SANKEI SHIMBUN reported Tuesday. 
  Quoting both Japanese and American diplomatic sources, the 
newspaper said the idea had been put to Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata by U.S. Vice President Al Gore during last week's meeting 
in Marrakech, Morocco, to sign the Uruguay Round trade accord. 
  Gore, noting that North Korea's nuclear program has a 
greater 
impact on Japan's security than his own country's, suggested 
that the United States might impose sanctions on its own if 
North Korea failed to permit additional IAEA (International 
Atomic Energy Agency) inspections of its suspected nuclear sites 
by the end of April, the report said. 
  Foreign Minister Hata told the vice president that Japan 
would examine the plan but did not give him an immediate answer 
in view of the need for the ruling coalition to first coordinate 
policy differences among its member parties in naming a new 
prime minister to replace the outgoing Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Entering the equation is a demand made by Shinseito, a major 
party in the coalition, which called for strong measures Monday 
to deal with the North Korean nuclear issue, it added. But a 
basic strategy proposed by the Nihon Shinto, another party of 
the coalition, urges "responsible Japanese action according to 
U.N. policy" in handling the issue: This would preclude 
Japanese cooperation in any U.S. sanctions imposed before U.N. 
action. 
  Shinseito's Ichiro Ozawa, a behind-the-scenes strongman in 
the coalition, met Foreign Minister Hata -- a likely bet to 
succeed Hosokawa as prime minister -- at the latter's office on 
Tuesday, raising speculation that they discussed dealing with 
North Korea when Hata becomes prime minister. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

