<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iraqi Foreign Minister Continues Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iraqi Foreign Minister Continues Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Seeks End of UN Economic Sanctions </H4>

<F P=102> BK1804160094 Jakarta ANTARA in English 1444 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK1804160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta ANTARA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jakarta, Apr 18 (ANTARA) -- Iraqi President Saddam 
Husayn is asking Indonesia as chairman of the Nonaligned 
Movement (NAM) to help settle the problem of continuing United 
Nations' economic sanctions against his country, Foreign 
Minister Ali Alatas said here on Monday. 
  "Iraq maintains that the sanctions should have been stopped 
long ago as Baghdad has complied with all UN Security Council 
resolutions including those on non-proliferation of nuclear and 
chemical weapons," the minister told the press after a meeting 
with visiting Iraqi Foreign Minister Sa'id al-Sahhaf. 
  Alatas said a letter from the Iraqi President containing the 
request would be handed to President Suharto by Sahhaf on 
Tuesday. 
  He said Indonesia had been closely following developments 
involving Iraq and made informal approaches to other NAM member 
countries to collect their views on Iraq's stance that it had 
implemented all of the Security Council's resolutions. 
  "We have the impression that Iraq has carried out all 
resolutions adopted by the UN Security Council. Yet the UN 
economic sanctions have continued to be in force," Alatas said. 
  "Indonesia as chairman of NAM will certainly attend to 
matter 
and, after an in-depth study, make efforts to help resolve it," 
Alatas said, adding that all decisions on the steps NAM would 
take to help Iraq would be made by President Suharto. 

</TEXT>

