<H3> <TI>   Envoy States PRC Stand on DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Envoy States PRC Stand on DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904124894 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 April 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1904124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Delivering a lecture at a Tokyo hotel on 18 April, 
Chinese Ambassador to Japan Xu Dunxin referred to China's role 
concerning the issue of North Korea's suspected development of 
nuclear weapons. He stressed: "The issue should be settled 
between the parties concerned. The international community 
should not expect too much from China." In this way he 
indicated that there is certain limitation to China's role. 
  The ambassador made it clear that China's basic position 
that 
the Korean peninsula should be denuclearized and nuclear 
inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
should be carried out remains unchanged. But he added: "The 
issue should be settled through patient dialogue, and we do not 
agree to the idea of applying pressure, such as economic 
sanctions," thus holding a move toward imposing economic 
sanctions against North Korea in check. 

</TEXT>

