<H3> <TI>   Murayama Opposes Proposed Laws on DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Murayama Opposes Proposed Laws on DPRK Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904041394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0324 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1904041394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 KYODO -- The head of the largest 
party in the ruling coalition reiterated opposition Tuesdayto 
proposed legislation to deal with emergencies that could stem 
from North Korea's refusal to fully open its nuclear facilities 
for inspection. 
  "We have to make utmost efforts within the constraints of 
the 
pacifist Constitution," said Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the 
Social Democratic Party, who spoke to reporters at a Tokyo hotel. 
  Murayama's remarks followed disagreement Monday during talks 
among representatives of the coalition parties over Japan's 
stance toward North Korea's suspected nuclear weapons 
development program. 
  During the talks, Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of core 
coalition party Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], proposed 
establishing domestic legislation in preparation for a possible 
naval blockade of North Korea. 
  Ozawa reportedly told the meeting, "Unless Japan prepares 
its 
domestic laws beforehand for a quick response to the situation 
such as a naval blockade, Japan would not be able to do anything 
at a time of contingency." 
  The SDP opposed the legislation, saying it would contravene 
Japan's longtime constitutional interpretation that it is not 
allowed to commit its military for collective military action, 
even to defend its security. 
  Murayama also told reporters, "It is a prerequisite to make 
utmost efforts through negotiations (with North Korea) to 
prevent such a contingency from breaking out." 
  Meanwhile, Murayama called on other coalition partners to 
speed up the process of naming a successor to outgoing Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  "We have to launch a new government as quickly as possible 
and we must conduct preparations to call a parliamentary 
election to name the new head of government tomorrow," he said. 
  Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, who is head of Shinseito, has 
emerged as the most likely replacement for Hosokawa, who 
announced on April 8 that he will step down over an alleged 
financial scandal and delays in Diet deliberations on the fiscal 
1994 budget. 

</TEXT>

