<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Army Members in DPRK View Tokyo Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Red Army Members in DPRK View Tokyo Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1704023394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0221 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1704023394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 17 KYODO -- Japan Red Army members 
living in Pyongyang since their 1970 hijacking of a Japan 
Airlines (JAL) airliner have slammed Tokyo's policies toward 
North Korea's suspected nuclear arms development program. 
  In a letter obtained Saturday [16 April] by KYODO NEWS 
SERVICE, the Red Army members remarked, "As a neighboring 
nation, Japan should not be conspiring with the United States 
but making efforts for dialogue and peace (with North Korea)." 
  The letter indicated that a declaration with the same 
content 
was sent to an influential member of the government's ruling 
coalition. 
  The U.S., along with Seoul and Tokyo, has been urging 
Pyongyang to comply with international nuclear safeguards 
accords and permit inspections of its nuclear facilities 
suspected of being part of an arms development program. 
  The U.S. has lobbied for a U.N. resolution calling for North 
Korea's compliance with the inspections, but at China's urging 
last month, the U.N. Security Council adopted a nonbinding 
presidential statement asking Pyongyang to be more open with its 
program. 
  With discussion about possibly imposing economic sanctions 
on 
North Korea under way in the United Nations, Japanese national 
security authorities suggested the letter was part of a 
propaganda campaign against Japan in connection with last 
Friday's 82nd birthday of North Korean leader Kim Il-song. 
  In 1970, nine Japan Red Army members commandeered a JAL 
Boeing 727, known as "Yodo," to Pyongyang. One of the hijackers 
has since died in North Korea and another was arrested in 1988 
while trying to return to Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

