<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Urges Tokyo To Promote Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Keidanren Urges Tokyo To Promote Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1804104894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1027 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1804104894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 18 KYODO -- The powerful Federation of 
Economic Organizations (Keidanren) called on the government on 
Monday [18 April] to promote deregulation, including phased 
abolition of the law regulating the opening of large-scale 
retail stores. 
  The federation also sought an easing of regulations on rice 
and liquor sales and railway fares. 
  The government maintains tight controls on licensing rice 
retailers. 
  The federation expressed hope that its appeal will be 
reflected in a deregulation program to be formulated by the 
government by the end of fiscal 1994. 
  It said deregulation in the retail business will help narrow 
the price gap between domestic and imported goods. 
  The federation said passenger and freight fares should be 
decontrolled while the existing regulation on shipbuilding 
should also be reviewed to allow newcomers to enter the coastal 
shipping market. 

</TEXT>

