<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Declines To Express Intentions 17 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Declines To Express Intentions 17 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1704103294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1007 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1704103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 17 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata, a front-runner to succeed outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, said Sunday [17 April] that he will formally express 
his decision after ruling coalition partners fine-tune their 
policies and pick him to run in the race for premier. 
  Hata, head of the coalition's core party Shinseito (Japan 
Renewal Party), made the remarks to reporters on a plane while 
returning to Japan from Marrakech, Morocco. 
  Hata was in Morocco to attend a four-day ministerial meeting 
of General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) member nations 
to sign the final agreement of the Uruguay Round of multilateral 
trade talks. 
  Regarding prospects that the coalition parties will endorse 
him as a replacement to Hosokawa, Hata, who is also deputy 
premier, declined to directly express any intention to be a 
candidate, only saying, "I will hear the views of other 
(coalition) partners...I'm not in a position to speak about 
specific matters." 
  On changing the framework of the current coalition, Hata 
said, "There are many moves within the (primary opposition) 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). A big move has not yet emerged. 
It will get clearer from tomorrow on what kind of framework 
(we) will establish." 
  The remark was apparently in reference to former Foreign 
Minister Michio Watanabe, an LDP veteran, who is eyeing forming 
ties with coalition parties, possibly Shinseito and Komeito, the 
alliance's other key party, to achieve his ambition of 
succeeding Hosokawa, political sources said. 
  The present seven-party coalition is made up of parties 
ranging from socialists to conservatives. 
  "In order to employ politics with responsibility, it is 
desirable that a force or a framework be formed capable of 
rivaling the LDP," Hata said. 
  Hata hinted at a possible tie-up with Watanabe, who has 
expressed his readiness to run for the upcoming Diet vote for 
the premiership to replace Hosokawa. Hosokawa announced his 
resignation on April 8 over questions regarding his personal 
finances. 
  Watanabe said Sunday he will leave the party to run in the 
prime ministerial election. 
  Hata told reporters at Tokyo's Haneda airport, "I would like 
to respect his determination. He is fit to be leader." 
  Five ruling coalition parties Monday are expected to 
fine-tune agreement on such key policies as tax reform and their 
stance on North Korea's suspected nuclear weapons development 
program. 
  The meeting will precede coalition leaders' talks on 
cementing the accords and then picking a successor to Hosokawa. 

</TEXT>

