<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fail To Reach Accord on Platform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fail To Reach Accord on Platform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904105494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1047 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1904105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 KYODO -- Representatives of the 
ruling coalition parties failed to agree on a policy platform 
Tuesday [19 April] for forming a new government to replace the 
cabinet of outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  The representatives resumed discussions on Tuesday morning 
to 
hammer out differences on two issues of immediate concern -- 
Japan's stance on North Korea's suspected nuclear arms 
development program and tax system reform -- before nominating a 
candidate for the premiership, party officials said. 
  They reached an accord on the North Korean nuclear issue but 
failed to narrow differences over tax reform, the officials said. 
  It now seems that Deputy Prime Minister and concurrently 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata is a virtual certainty to be 
elected the next prime minister. Michio Watanabe, an 
influential figure in the opposition Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP), formally gave up his notion Tuesday to leave the party in 
a bid to seek the premiership, hoping to gain the support of the 
coalition. 
  Watanabe, 70, conveyed his decision in a third meeting with 
LDP President Yohei Kono, who has himself vowed to run in a Diet 
election to select a successor to Hosokawa, 56, who abruptly 
announced his resignation on April 8 on account of his financial 
improprieties. 
  The coalition representatives will resume talks Wednesday 
and 
the selection of Hata as a prime ministerial candidate by the 
coalition chiefs was postponed to as early as Wednesday, they 
said. 
  As a result, a Diet election to nominate Hosokawa's 
successor 
will take place as early as Thursday, parliamentary sources said. 
  Hata said Monday cabinet changes must be minimal after the 
establishment of a new government. 
  On the North Korean nuclear problem, the representatives 
agreed Japan should be prepared under the framework of the 
Constitution for an emergency situation. 
  The agreement reached said Japan would adhere to the 
policies 
of the United Nations, and "the government should be prepared 
under the framework of the Constitution for an emergency 
situation." 
  It also said Japan should cooperate closely with the United 
States and South Korea. 
  Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], which is led by Hata, has 
called for a tougher stance against North Korea and urged a 
revision of current laws, if necessary, to implement possible 
economic sanctions against North Korea. 
  The Social Democratic Party (SDP), the largest party in the 
seven-party coalition, has voiced its opposition to sanctions. 
Japan's Constitution renounces the use of force to settle 
international disputes. 
  As for tax reform, Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa, 
the chief strategist in the eight-month-old coalition, proposed 
a sweeping tax reform centered on an indirect tax hike. 
  SDP Secretary General Wataru Kubo rejected the proposal, 
party officials said. The SDP has opposed the current 3 percent 
consumption tax on almost all goods and services. 
  Hosokawa was forced to withdraw his plan in early February 
to 
introduce a fresh 7 percent "national welfare tax" to replace 
the consumption tax after facing stiff opposition from the SDP, 
which threatened to withdraw from the coalition. 
  The representatives were from the level of secretary general 
of the SDP, Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party), Komeito, the Japan 
New Party (JNP), the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), the 
Democratic Reform Party, a small parliamentary group in the 
House of Councillors, and Kaikaku no Kai (Reform Society), a 
small parliamentary group of LDP defectors in the House of 
Representatives. 
  New party Sakigake (Harbinger), a small component in the 
coalition, which declared Friday that it will not take a post in 
the new cabinet because of disappointment over the issue of 
picking a successor to Hosokawa, did not attend the session. 
  Sakigake led by Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura 
has said it will support the candidate agreed upon by the 
coalition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

