<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nikkeiren Chief on Political Stability Return </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nikkeiren Chief on Political Stability Return </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904091694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0911 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1904091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 KYODO -- An influential business 
leader expressed hope Tuesday [19 April] that political 
stability will be restored with the likely selection of Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata as successor to departing Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Takeshi Nagano, president of the Japan Federation of 
Employers' Associations (Nikkeiren), was commenting on news 
reports the ruling coalition is expected to choose Hata as 
Hosokawa's successor. 
  The new administration is expected to pursue the line 
followed by the Hosokawa government, and its foundations will be 
more stable than present ones, he said. 
  The government will do its utmost to enact the 1994 fiscal 
budget, up for parliamentary approval, as soon as possible, 
Nagano said. 
  He said the yen's appreciation has hampered economic 
recovery, and its value should be lowered to a level matching 
its purchasing power to help ease the impact on domestic 
industry. 
  There are bright signs of recovery but they have yet to 
cover 
all industries, he said. 

</TEXT>

