Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Discusses Economic Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Discusses Economic Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904030194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0223 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1904030194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 KYODO -- The recent uptrend in 
long-term interest rates will top the agenda at a spate of 
international meetings later this month in Washington, Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii said Tuesday. 
  Fujii, speaking at a regular news conference after a morning 
cabinet meeting, declined to comment on the overnight tightening 
of U.S. credit policy, however. 
  Finance ministers and central bankers from the Group of 
Seven 
(G-7) major industrialized nations are slated to meet Sunday in 
Washington for twice-yearly gatherings through Tuesday of the 
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank. 
  "I presume interest rates will become one of the major 
issues," Fujii said, noting that sustainable growth without 
inflation is what G-7 nations want to attain. 
  Fujii acknowledged there were various views concerning the 
tighter U.S. credit stance, such as increasing hopes for an 
economic recovery and spreading fears of inflation. 
  But he said, "I shouldn't be commenting on another nation's 
credit policy." 
  The U.S. Federal Reserve Board announced overnight a slight 
tightening of its credit policy, lifting the target rate for the 
federal funds rate by a quarter of a percentage point. 
  The third tightening since the Fed changed its credit stance 
for the first time in five years in February contrasts with 
Germany's move last week to cut its key rates to allow other 
European nations to follow suit. 
  The U.S. credit stance has sent long-term market rates 
sharply higher, exporting the uptrend to other G-7 nations. 
  With a credit policy gap surfacing between the U.S., which 
is 
on the road to recovery, and Japan and some European nations 
which are still struggling with sluggish economies, coordination 
is expected to become a tough issue for the G-7 meeting. 
  Concerning Japan's huge trade surplus that is certain to be 
another major topic, Fujii declined to suggest remedies, saying 
it depends on the coming new cabinet. 
  Japan is set to choose a new prime minister, with the most 
likely candidate being Foreign Minister and Deputy Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, to succeed Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa who offered to resign earlier this month. 
  Fujii said he does not know whether Japan will be 
represented 
at the Washington meetings by its finance minister in view of 
the uncertain political situation and the expected start of Diet 
debate on the fiscal 1994 budget as soon as a new cabinet is 
formed. 
  Referring to the fiscal 1993 trade surplus released Monday, 
Fujii said exports are decreasing and imports are increasing in 
terms of volume. The trend shows the effectiveness of the Trade 
Ministry's measures, he said. 
  Japan's trade surplus for the year ended March 31 hit a 
record high for the second year in a row, reaching 121.99 
billion dollars, up 10.0 percent from the year before. 
  Fujii said Japan will continue taking action to boost 
domestic demand and deregulatory steps to facilitate market 
access as included in the February stimulus package and the 
March market-opening plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

