<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Matsuura Claims U.S. Shift on Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Matsuura Claims U.S. Shift on Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204075594 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 22 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2204075594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 22 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] In his speech in Tokyo on 21 April, Koichiro 
Matsuura, deputy vice minister of foreign affairs until 
recently, commented on the meeting between Deputy Prime Minister 
and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and U.S. Trade Representative 
(USTR) Mickey Kantor on 15 April. He said, "Although prospects 
remain uncertain for resuming the Japan-U.S. economic framework 
talks, the minutes of the meeting show that at various points in 
his remarks, Mr. Kantor showed his willingness to work for 
setting the framework talks in order." He thus indicated that 
there has been a change in the U.S. position. 
  With regard to the resumption of the talks, he said, "Both 
Japan and the United States have to come up with ideas on how to 
formulate the objective criteria. They should narrow their gap 
through behind-the-scenes contacts." He stressed the need to 
come up with points of compromise through unofficial discussions. 
  On the issue of reducing Japan's current accounts surplus, 
Matsuura reiterated that "Japan should not set a numerical 
target." He pointed out that "what is important is to adopt 
policies which will produce actual results in reducing the 
surplus in each quarter of the year." 
  As to the microeconomic sectors, he said, "If possible, 
measures, even in the financial services and other non-priority 
sectors, should be compiled before July." 

</TEXT>

