<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows `Apprehension' on DPRK Nuclear Arms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows `Apprehension' on DPRK Nuclear Arms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104141494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2104141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A nationwide poll conducted by YOMIURI SHIMBUN on 
16 and 17 April revealed that 70 percent of the people feel 
uneasy about North Korea's suspected nuclear arms development. 
The number of respondents who answered that they would 
"support" Japan's decision to cooperate with the United Nations 
in imposing sanctions against North Korea if it continues to 
reject nuclear inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA), and if the United Nations decides to take some 
kind of sanction, totaled 60 percent. 
  How to deal with the issue of North Korea's suspected 
nuclear 
arms development has become the most important task confronting 
Japan. It is also a focal point of policy discussions among the 
ruling coalition parties. However, the poll indicated that the 
people are highly interested in this issue, and many of them are 
of the view that the international community, with the United 
Nations as the central figure, should take a decisive stand 
against North Korea. 
  As for the issue of North Korea's suspected nuclear arms 
development, the total of respondents who answered they were 
"very much interested" or "somewhat interested" reached 70 
percent, exceeding by far the 27 percent who answered they were 
"not so much" or "completely not" interested. 
  As for apprehension about suspected nuclear arms 
development, 
as many as 71 percent of those surveyed answered they "feel it," 
and only 23 percent said they "do not feel it." As regards the 
question of whether Japan should cooperate with the United 
Nations in imposing sanctions against North Korea, 60 percent 
said they would "support" and 24 percent said they would "not 
support" the government's decision to cooperate. 
  It seems the people are highly interested in and feel 
apprehensive about the issue due to the fact that, in addition 
to Japanese disapproval of and precautions against nuclear 
weapons, North Korea has developed missiles which can strike 
most parts of Japan. 
  Asked why they supported Japan's cooperation in imposing UN 
sanctions, 42 percent--the highest rate--said that North Korea's 
nuclear development is a "threat to Japan's security." This was 
followed by 31 percent who said North Korean nuclear arms 
development "runs counter to international trends, including 
reductions of nuclear weapons" and by 14 percent who said "North 
Korean is ignoring UN agreements." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6536 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas078__a94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-078-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Support for Hata as Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Support for Hata as Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104140894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2104140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] While political parties have been engaged in the 
final coordination of selecting a successor to outgoing Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, YOMIURI SHIMBUN conducted a 
nationwide opinion poll on 16-17 April to sound out the trend of 
public support for "Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata" and the 
people's view on various issues, including Hosokawa's 
resignation announcement. A majority of the respondents 
indicated support for "Prime Minister Hata." For example, 61 
percent said they would "support" Hata if he becomes the next 
premier, while only 21 percent said they would "not support" 
him. As for Hosokawa's resignation announcement, 60 percent of 
the respondents said "he is irresponsible"; this number exceeded 
the proportion of those who said "he acted with good grace in 
announcing his intention to step down." These results indicate 
the people's strong criticism of Hosokawa for suddenly giving up 
the administration. At the same time, 57 percent of the 
respondents said they "wanted Hosokawa to remain in power." 
This number exceeded by 20 points the 37 percent of respondents 
who said "there was a good reason for him to step down," 
indicating Hosokawa is still popular among people. In addition, 
65 percent spoke highly of the achievements made by the Hosokawa 
administration during the past eight months. 
  The 61 percent support rate for Hata is high, exceeding the 
nonsupport rate by 40 points. We cannot compare it with the 
support rate for the Hosokawa cabinet because the figure is not 
an actual support rate for a Hata cabinet. However, it is 
higher than the support rate for the Hosokawa cabinet (55.1 
percent) in the survey conducted last March. Thus, the poll 
revealed the strong hopes the people place on "Prime Minister 
Hata." 
  Moreover, regarding the question of "who is the most 
appropriate person to be the next prime minister?" Hata ranked 
highest with a 37-percent approval rating. This compared with 
12 percent for former Deputy Prime Minister Michio Watanabe of 
the Liberal Democratic Party [LDP], who was regarded as a 
probable candidate at the time of the poll. These ratings are 
followed by 7 percent for former Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu 
and 4 percent each for Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi 
Takemura, LDP Policy Research Council Chairman Ryutaro 
Hashimoto, and LDP President Yohei Kono. 
  As for the most desirable composition of the next 
government, 
respondents answered as follow: 1) an administration composed 
of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], Komeito, the Japan New 
Party, and a portion of the LDP (28 percent of the respondents); 
2) the same administration led by the current coalition, 
excluding the LDP and the Japan Communist Party (21 percent); 
3) an administration composed of the Social Democratic Party of 
Japan, the Democratic Socialist Party, Sakigake [Harbinger], and 
a portion of the LDP (15 percent); and 4) an administration 
composed mainly of the LDP (14 percent). 
  In response to Hosokawa's resignation announcement, 60 
percent said "it was irresponsible" while 35 percent said "he 
acted with good grace." 
  Regarding accomplishments made during the past eight months 
of the Hosokawa administration, 65 percent of the respondents 
said "it can be highly evaluated" while 31 percent said "it 
cannot." As specific achievements to be noted, 37 percent said 
"the Hosokawa government put an end to the LDP one-party 
administration"; 34 percent cited "it raised people's political 
consciousness"; and another 34 percent said "it enacted 
political reform-related bills." 
  On the other hand, the poll also revealed the people's 
negative attitude towards the Hosokawa administration. 
Criticism was mostly centered on Hosokawa's lack of decisive 
policies and power struggles within the administration. For 
example, 35 percent of the respondents said "Hosokawa often 
retracted his decisions on important issues"; 33 percent noted 
"Shinseito coleader Ichiro Ozawa had too much influence upon the 
administration"; and 32 percent said "there were too many 
discords and conflicts within the administration." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

